{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:47:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:47:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15519"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15519"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.03,0.05,0.46,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8210"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9895"},{"type":"tags","id":"9906"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19864"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) presents with different classical phenotypes - for example, emphysema and chronic bronchitis. These were historically called \u0022pink puffers\u0022 and \u0022blue bloaters\u0022. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about COPD is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patients with emphysema have preserved ventilatory response to blood gases","Airflow obstruction in COPD is fully reversible","Chronic bronchitis results in normal blood oxygen levels","Emphysematous lungs have reduced compliance","Chronic bronchitis includes a reduction in mucus production"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn COPD, there are several different phenotypes with distinct pathophysiological patterns. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmphysema predominant (\u0022pink puffers\u0022) \u003C/strong\u003Epatients have a\u003Cstrong\u003E preserved ventilatory response to blood gases\u003C/strong\u003E, leading to compensatory hyperventilation and use of accessory muscles. They appear pink due to their maintained oxygenation through increased work of breathing. The lungs in emphysema have \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased compliance\u003C/strong\u003E due to destruction of the elastic tissue. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic bronchitis predominant (\u0022blue bloaters\u0022) \u003C/strong\u003Epatients\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Etypically have\u003Cstrong\u003E low oxygen levels \u003C/strong\u003Eand develop secondary polycythaemia, giving them a cyanotic appearance. They experience chronic \u003Cstrong\u003Emucus hypersecretion\u003C/strong\u003E, defined as productive cough for at least three months in two consecutive years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAirflow obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E in COPD is characteristically fixed and progressive, unlike asthma where it is typically reversible. This is due to permanent structural changes in the airways and lung parenchyma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic bronchitis (\u0027blue bloaters\u0027) and emphysema (\u0027pink puffers\u0027) have distinct pathophysiological patterns","Airflow obstruction in COPD is characteristically fixed and progressive"],"references":["Rodrigues SO, Cunha CMCD, Soares GMV, Silva PL, Silva AR, Gon\u00e7alves-de-Albuquerque CF. Mechanisms, Pathophysiology and Currently Proposed Treatments of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease. Pharmaceuticals (Basel). 2021 Sep 26;14(10):979. doi: 10.3390/ph14100979. PMID: 34681202; PMCID: PMC8539950.","Spurzem JR, Rennard SI. Pathogenesis of COPD. Semin Respir Crit Care Med. 2005 Apr;26(2):142-53. doi: 10.1055/s-2005-869535. PMID: 16088433.","Leap J, Arshad O, Cheema T, Balaan M. Pathophysiology of COPD. Crit Care Nurs Q. 2021 Jan/Mar;44(1):2-8. doi: 10.1097/CNQ.0000000000000334. PMID: 33234854.","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51291"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15519"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51291"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:47:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:47:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8210"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"